module sys.durability;

// =============================================================================
// core/sys/durability.vr — Crash-safe persistence primitives (public API)
// =============================================================================
// Layer: 0 (Core)
// Spec: internal/specs/sqlite-native.md §3.2 Gap 2
//
// Thin, named re-export surface over the durability primitives already
// living in `core.sys.common`. The spec names a dedicated module so
// callers declare their intent at the import site
// (`mount core.sys.durability.{full_fsync, sync_directory}`) instead of
// having to reach into the catch-all `common` namespace.
//
// No new behaviour is introduced here. The underlying implementations
// in `common.vr` remain the single source of truth; this module merely
// exports them through a stable, intent-named surface. Platform backends:
//
//   * Linux   — `fsync(fd)` / `fsync(dirfd)` via direct syscall
//   * Darwin  — `fcntl(fd, F_FULLFSYNC)` via libSystem
//   * Windows — `FlushFileBuffers(handle)` via kernel32
//
// The `sync_directory` wrapper opens the directory read-only, fsyncs it,
// closes it — required on POSIX after rename/unlink/creat for the
// name-change to survive power-loss. On Windows it is a no-op because
// NTFS journals directory updates synchronously in the FS layer.
// =============================================================================

mount core.sys.common;

// Public surface — stable names, same behaviour as the backends in common.
public mount core.sys.common.full_fsync;
public mount core.sys.common.sync_directory;
public mount core.sys.common.pread;
public mount core.sys.common.pwrite;
public mount core.sys.common.FileDesc;
public mount core.sys.common.OSError;
